When skills are underused, motivation disappears.
A company that fails to recognize talent wastes both its time and its peopleâ€™s potential.


Below what make developer frustrated when they join a new company:

 Misaligned Roles: Hired for one skill set, assigned to another.

 Underchallenging Work: Tasks donâ€™t match their abilities.

 No Growth: Limited learning or development opportunities.

 Skill Blindness: Leadership unaware of their full potential.

 Tool Restrictions: Forced to use outdated or rigid tools.

 No Autonomy: Creativity and expertise stifled.

 Unrecognized Strengths: Skills overlooked or undervalued.

Solutions for Better Utilization:

Skill Mapping: Regularly assess each developerâ€™s skills and match them to tasks that align with their strengths.

Provide Growth Opportunities: Offer challenges and learning resources to help developers grow.

Flexible Project Assignments: Let developers explore tasks outside their current role when they show interest or potential.

Involve Developers in Decisions: When possible, let developers propose and choose tools or approaches.

comments.commentText:
Interesting paradigm shift to consider. Agree fully that gaining operating leverage while scaling is top of mind for operators and reducing support cost is likely one of the clearest vectors for accomplishing that (good case could also be made for being more scrupulous of GTM spend/GTM efficiency but thatâ€™s a separate convo). I am curious, though, about a couple of points on this issueâ€¦
1. How far along this curve are some of the biggest incumbents? 2. What (if any) variance is seen by customers vis-a-vis resolution? If de minimis, this is obv highly compelling. If de minimis but lack of human interaction is perceived as lower value, the calculus gets a little murkier as possible attribution to other factors gets harder to calculate cleanly when more of this is offloaded from human headcount. 3. It seems many are making similar claims about resolution efficacy/efficiency but I suspect as with many metrics reported by nascent applications of bleeding age tech there is likely much noise in the data or the value prop to customers less clear than is being told. Net net I think itâ€™s a great short term narrative in a drive toward profitability companies who need to improve margin.

Longer term, Iâ€™m curious/skeptical about the tradeoffs from moving too quickly down this path from a churn standpoint, especially for higher end enterprise saas and for lower end SMB SaaS. Itâ€™s reminiscent of much of the same narrative that was pitched regarding chatbots and how game changing they would be. Those helped unlocked scale but also caused a lot of frustration with customers. Will be curious how companies balance these tradeoffs. From the way many seem to be framing approach I suspect it will be brand dilutive and very frustrating to customers who likely already have fatigue toward the customer experience (or lackthereof). Jason of Saastr just did a pod where he discussed some of the narrative messaging around AI resolution efficacy from large incumbents (e.g., Zendesk and others) and it seems everyone is beating a similar drum. Will be curious to see who ultimately wins and what hybrid balance they strike.
